⚡ Asynchronous Middleware

If your project uses async views, you can write async middleware too.

Async Function Middleware
from asgiref.sync import iscoroutinefunction
from django.utils.decorators import sync_and_async_middleware

@sync_and_async_middleware
def simple_middleware(get_response):
    if iscoroutinefunction(get_response):
        async def middleware(request):
            print("Async request")
            response = await get_response(request)
            return response
    else:
        def middleware(request):
            print("Sync request")
            response = get_response(request)
            return response
    return middleware

Async Class Middleware
from asgiref.sync import iscoroutinefunction, markcoroutinefunction

class AsyncMiddleware:
    async_capable = True
    sync_capable = False

    def __init__(self, get_response):
        self.get_response = get_response
        if iscoroutinefunction(get_response):
            markcoroutinefunction(self)

    async def __call__(self, request):
        print("Async Middleware")
        response = await self.get_response(request)
        return response

🏛 Old vs New Middleware (pre Django 1.10)

Old ones used MIDDLEWARE_CLASSES and methods like:

process_request

process_response

To make them work in new Django, use MiddlewareMixin:

from django.utils.deprecation import MiddlewareMixin

class OldStyleMiddleware(MiddlewareMixin):
    def process_request(self, request):
        print("Old style request")

    def process_response(self, request, response):
        print("Old style response")
        return response

Middleware = filters around views (onion model).

Can be function or class.

Add to MIDDLEWARE in settings.py.

Special hooks: process_view, process_exception, process_template_response.

Supports sync + async.

Use MiddlewareMixin for old style.
